## Part 4: Messaging Don'ts (The Anti-Patterns)

### Don't lead with compliance
Compliance is an outcome, not the product. Leading with compliance limits you to organizations that already know they have a compliance problem. Leading with security + operations captures everyone building agents, regardless of regulatory awareness.

**Wrong:** "EU AI Act compliance for AI agents"
**Right:** "Your AI agents are powerful. Are they safe?"

### Don't compare yourself to LLM safety tools
Lakera, NeMo Guardrails, and LLM Guard operate at the model layer — preventing prompt injection and jailbreaks. Suprawall operates at the execution layer — governing what agents can DO. These are different things. Don't position against them; position alongside them.

**Wrong:** "Better than Lakera at prompt injection detection"
**Right:** "Lakera protects the model. Suprawall protects the world the model touches."

### Don't try to sell all six features at once
Each buyer cares about different features. The developer cares about the Vault and budget controls. The CTO cares about the dashboard and approval workflows. The compliance officer cares about the audit trail and PDF report. Let each buyer discover the features relevant to them.

**Wrong:** Homepage listing all 6 features with equal emphasis to a generic audience
**Right:** Homepage showing the universal hook ("one line of code, every tool call governed") then letting visitors self-select into their pain point

### Don't use fear without providing the fix
Your current messaging is strong on threats (which is good) but always pair the threat with the solution in the same breath. A reader who feels fear without a clear path to resolution will close the tab, not sign up.

**Wrong:** "94% of system prompts are bypassable" (and then moving to a different section)
**Right:** "94% of system prompts are bypassable. Suprawall doesn't rely on prompts — it enforces policies deterministically at the SDK level."

### Don't say "trusted by" without proof
Your current homepage says "Trusted by AI engineers shipping LangChain, CrewAI, AutoGen, and Vercel AI to production." If you can't show logos, names, or numbers — remove this line. Unverified social proof damages credibility more than no social proof.

Replace with: "Built for LangChain, CrewAI, AutoGen, and Vercel AI agents" — this describes compatibility, not trust, and doesn't require proof.